        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="5">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage or personal injury, or both, possibly death, do not perform service
                        on the fuel system in the presence of open flames, intense heat, sparks, lighted cigarettes, or
                        similar hazards in your work area.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <para>Repairing, lengthening, shortening or adding additional fuel lines will require installation of the
                Voss fuel line connectors. Typical compression fittings will not work on the factory installed diesel
                fuel hose.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Precautions:</emph>
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Use a hose material suitable for use with diesel fuel (Synflex air brake hose is
                        suitable).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Carry out procedure at room temperature.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Do not heat hose.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Hose barb (fir-tree) on Voss connector must be undamaged to permit tight
                        connection.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Hose barb (fir-tree) and hose must be clean and free of any lubricant.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Cut the end of the hose cleanly at 90&#176; to the longitudinal axis of the hose.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clamp the hose into the corresponding size hole in a die block from a brake line flaring
                    tool set, approximately 1 inch from the cut end. Brake line flaring tool sets are available from
                    your hand tool supplier. Choose one that accommodates &#189;" and 5/8" O.D. tubing. See Figure 1.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0415011" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g0115021.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Brake Line Flaring Die Block</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start a straight or 90&#176; Voss connector into the end of the hose. Do not use any
                    lubricant. See Figure 2 and Figure 3.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0415012" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g0115022.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Installing Straight Barbed Connector Using an Arbor Press</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0415013" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g0115023.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Installing 90&#176; Barbed Connector Using an Arbor Press</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If installing a straight male connector, make sure protective dust cap is in place or
                    insert a protective washer and bolt into the connector. See Figure 4.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0415014" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g0115024.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Installing Straight Barbed Connector Using Large Channel-lock type Pliers</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If installing a straight female connector, use a male cap for protection (see parts
                    listing). Alternatively, insert a protective washer and bolt into connector, making sure not to
                    cause any damage to the o-ring sealing surface.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0415015" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g0115025.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Installing 90&#176; Barbed Connector Using Large Channel-lock type Pliers</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using an arbor press (see Figures 2 and 3), drill press (insert protective bolt into
                    drill chuck) or large channel lock type pliers (see Figures 4 and 5), press the connector straight
                    into the hose until the connector is fully inserted. Do not press connector in at an angle. An arbor
                    press is preferred over channel-lock type pliers.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The o-ring and its corresponding sealing surfaces on both the male and female connectors
                    must be free of dirt, debris, cuts and nicks to avoid leakage.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Voss connectors snap together by hand. To disconnect a Voss connector, squeeze the white
                    plastic lock-release and pull apart.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fuel lines must be routed and secured so that there are no bending, torsional or
                    vibrational loads on the Voss connectors. Cutting the hose and installing a straight pair of male
                    and female Voss connectors can eliminate torsional loads.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install fuel lines and operate engine to verify there are no leaks.</para>
            </step1>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Tool Information:</emph>
                In instances where a large number of fuel line connector installations are being performed, it may be
                desirable to purchase a special installation tool. For tool information, contact:
